The Sydney Opera House is a multi-venue performing arts centre in Sydney, Australia. It is one of the 20th century's most famous and distinctive buildings.[3] Designed by Danish architect JÃ¸rn Utzon, the building was formally opened on 20 October 1973[4] after a gestation beginning with Utzon's 1957 selection as winner of an international design competition. The government of New South Wales, led by the premier, Joseph Cahill, authorised work to begin in 1958 with Utzon directing construction. The government's decision to build Utzon's design is often overshadowed by circumstances that followed, including cost and scheduling overruns as well as the architect's ultimate resignation.[5 The building and its surrounds occupy the whole of Bennelong Point on Sydney Harbour, between Sydney Cove and Farm Cove, adjacent to the Sydney central business district and the Royal Botanic Gardens, and close by the Sydney Harbour Bridge. Though its name suggests a single venue, the building comprises multiple performance venues which together are among the busiest[citation needed] performing arts centres â€“ hosting well over 1,500 performances annually, attended by more than 1.2 million people.[6] Performances are presented by numerous performing artists, including four resident companies: Opera Australia, The Australian Ballet, the Sydney Theatre Company and the Sydney Symphony Orchestra. As one of the most popular visitor attractions in Australia, more than eight million people visit the site annually, and approximately 350,000 visitors take a guided tour of the building each year.[7] The building is managed by the Sydney Opera House Trust, an agency of the New South Wales State Government. @josiemarancosmetics product review: Josie Maran 100% pure argan oil is a multitasking wonder product, this oil can be used to hydrate, protect and heal nails, hair and skin. This oil is used for so many things, a drop is also enough to smooth out hair or soften dry and hard cuticles. Argan oil has a number of benefits when used on hair. It can act as a moisturiser for the scalp to fight dandruff and dry scalp or it even can be used as a hair mask! It can also promote the growth of healthy, strong hair as opposed to thin, brittle hair. It can even undo some of the damage done through chemical treatments and dyes, and can be used to treat split ends. For other users I also recommend patting it over the neck as well as massaging it onto rough and dry skin patches like the elbows, knees, hands and feet. You can also add a drop of this argan oil into your daily moisturizer prior to application to boost its moisturizing effect or even add a few drops of the Aragon oil to your foundation to help give that nice radiant dewy effect! This Oil doesn't leave that greasy oily effect which I absolutely love! When my skin is feeling really dry and flaky I add a few drops off this and massage it into my face onto my lips, lashes and eyebrows to promote growth for my lashes and brows and hydration for my lips over night only waking up the next morning to radiant plump soft hydrated skin! ğŸ’Hanging Out For Shoulder HealthğŸ’ ---------------------------------- The shoulder joint has the most range of motion out of any joint in the body which means it is capable of some pretty amazing and complex movements but because of this it is also one of the areas that is most commonly injured. And from experience having multiple shoulder dislocations and a grade 3 AC joint tear, I know that to be quite true! ----------------------------------A lot of shoulder injuries stem from the shoulder being too tight among other things. Hanging from a bar is a simple but very effective mobility exercise that I like to add into my client's training to help promote shoulder health, allow us to improve over head strength and stability and is also a great grip strengthening exercise. ---------------------------------- Simply grab hold of a chin up bar or anything else that is high enough and can support your body weight and allow your shoulders to relax and stretch out. Ideally doing several sets holding for 30 seconds or more to allow time for the muscle to stretch and create lasting change. The longer you hold the more grip strength endurance you will obviously need which will come in hand when the time comes to do chin ups. ---------------------------------- Like the squat mobility, practicing hanging for a few minutes everyday will help you create lasting change, allow you maintain that change you make and go a long way in helping prevent injuries. Because injuries suck!

Today I had a Body Composition Analysis completed! This is my second scan, and it's kind of a half way scan for me. I am planning on completing another BCA towards the end of the year to check my muscle gain and progress!  Between these 2 photos; - 111kgs to 89kgs, that's a loss of 22kgs! - Body Fat Percentage has gone from 59.8% to 36.7%! That's a total BFP loss of 23.1%! - BMI has gone from 37.1 (obese) to 29.2 (overweight)! That's a total BMI loss of 7.9! - My Visceral Fat level is currently 16, this level should be between 1-9, I still have to work on this number! I can't imagine what level it was at when I was 111kgs ğŸ˜³  When I completed my first BCA just under 2 years ago, I was told that if I did not change my lifestyle within the next 2 years, I would die at a very young age. I was 59.8% fat, and I had severe Visceral Fat (fat around your organs). I ignored this information for about a year, until finally 2016 rolled around and I realised I was very sick, I was very sore, and I was extremely scared. I decided enough was enough and I changed my life for me. I want to live a long and healthy life, I want to grow old with someone and create a family with someone. I want to be healthy enough to travel, go on adventures and keep up with my future kids. I want to feel healthy and happy within myself! I want to be stronger! I'm slowly battling through each and every day to become the best version of myself! ğŸ’ªğŸ»â¤ğŸº #love #happy #wicca #moonchild #spiritual #dedication #mentality #motivation #inspiration #fit #fitness #fitgirl #weights #gym #progress #weightloss #australia #sydney #worldgympenrith #booty #bulking #gains #squat #health #healthy #strong #lifestyle

Camping in the wild is often the most attractive option, many of the most gorgeous places in the world are thankfully far from five stars hotels . You need wild camping if you want to spend the night gazing stars & seeing wild animals . For many people the thought of wild camping is daunting , you may worry about trouble in the middle of the night from animals or hear an ant fart in the night ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ , if you are like this , camp with some experience campers or just give it time .  These types of fears are natural just build up your confidence slowly & dont get discouraged, these types of fears are natural , the more you camp out the more you ll realise how safe wild camping is. Steak tartare great too, and so was the raspberry soufflÃ© with wild berry gelato. Good wine list as well. I had a 2011 La Gardine Grenache-Syrah Chateauneuf du Pape, which matched perfectly with the beef. Also a very special father son get together, which has become an annual tradition.

#Sydney, capital of New South Wales and one of Australia's largest cities, is best known for its harbourfront Sydney Opera House, with a distinctive sail-like design. Massive Darling Harbour and the smaller Circular Quay port are hubs of waterside life, with the arched Harbour Bridge and esteemed Royal Botanic Garden nearby. Sydney Towerâ€™s outdoor platform, the Skywalk, offers 360-degree views of the city and suburbs. Sydney Aquarium, Taronga Zoo and Wildlife Sydney Zoo shelter animals like koalas, kangaroos, sharks and snakes. Pyrmontâ€™s Sydney Fish Market has a working seafood auction and restaurants serving the dayâ€™s catch. There are multicultural dining opportunities all over the city, including in Haymarketâ€™s Chinatown and the restaurants serving the Italian community in Leichhardt. A ferry ride through the harbour is part of the experience in visiting outer Sydney destinations such as Bondi and Manly Beaches â€“ both popular for surfing. - Perth, capital of Western Australia, sits where the Swan River meets the southwest coast. Sandy beaches line its suburbs, and the huge, riverside Kings Park and Botanic Garden on Mt. Eliza offer sweeping views of the city. The Perth Cultural Centre houses the state ballet and opera companies, and occupies its own central precinct, including a theatre, art galleries and the Western Australian Museum. Central Perth also has the interactive Scitech science centre, Perth Mintâ€™s displays of gold bars and nuggets, and Barrack Squareâ€™s glass Bell Tower, with its own viewing platform. Shopping is concentrated in pedestrianised Murray and Hay streets, with high-end boutiques on King Street. The neighbouring 19th-century port of Fremantle draws visitors to its craft markets, an 1850s prison and seafood restaurants in the Fishing Boat Harbour. The shoreline north of Perth is known as the Sunset Coast. It's home to family-friendly Cottesloe Beach, popular snorkelling site Marmion Marine Park and Trigg Beach, with large waves for surfing.

It's natural for people to get excited when they learn about my freelance life and my predominantly remote working lifestyle. â¤ Yes, it's great to be able to work from anywhere, it's allowed me to travel overseas without sacrificing on my work. But a lot of people also end up saying how it would be great to "stop working for the man" and how they're so over whatever it is they're doing and that the 9 to 5 mediocre life is shit. The thing is, I will never say that to anyone. ğŸ˜Š My lifestyle isn't for everyone - obviously I only post the fun things, but behind it all... I'm exhausted. I'm chasing every single day. My brain doesn't stop ticking. I've lost so much sleep. I've doubted my abilities. I'm ALWAYS scared about new things I have to do - but I do them because I just have to. I've been close to "giving up" at least once a month only to realise that I'm curious to see what else happens. At the same time, yes - I am free and happy. But like I said, it's not for everyone. The 9 to 5 at least has the stability and you won't have sleepless nights worrying about more things. You've got an expected income. Who knows? Maybe one day I'll end up back in some fulltime job. Maybe I won't. WHO KNOWS. ğŸ˜‚ If your 9 to 5 is shit, then do something about it. Make it better for yourself, but don't just complain and keep on living that way. And if you do want to be your own boss, then start working towards it - just remember that even if I'm my own boss, I have many clients that I have to keep happy so it's not that different. The reason I live and work the way I do is because I love searching for happiness and other ways of living, while making the most of every situation. Ok, the flexibility of being able to travel is great - but even I have to stay put in one place at a time to work. Isn't life crazy? 8 yrs ago this month, I was watching my whirlwind romance gasp its last breath. And I was watching my job do much the same.  7 yrs ago to the month, I was re-building a sense of home for the second time in six months, on the other side of the world away from all that I called familiar. I was having panic attacks in the street and weeping fits behind closed doors.  All of it led to the beginning of my beginning. Since then I've learned to roll with the lives and deaths within my own life better, watching chapters and doors open and close. And don't get me wrong, the transitions can still hurt like all hell but I'm learning.  Now? Now I understand that there are a few important priorities when it comes to change.  1. It is all too easy to identify the loss/ the thing falling away as part of you. It's not. It's part of your life but not part of you. You are just as whole and as complete and safe as you always have been.  2. When it comes to the final retrospective, it will be far more important how you handled things than what the things actually were. Your sense of self, strength, grace, compassion, growth isn't measured by the things that happen to/for you but how you navigate through them. And that includes being wise enough to ask for help when needed.  3. Assigning blame or sitting in shame is the quickest way of avoiding the learning available. Fixing your gaze on 'shoulda, woulda, coulda' lifts you right out of the present moment and all you can gain from it.  4. Don't mistake solitude for stillness. We all need quiet periods to absorb, digest and integrate the changes, especially introverts. But fear of the unknown can keep us there longer than actually supports us. Where possible, stick to some kind of routine that keeps you in the world just a little.  5. It's necessary to feel. That which we dampen biochemically nestles into our body and sets up home there. And that which we suppress entirely suppresses its happy counterpart too. Find someone or somewhere that allows you to safely work through the spectrum so that you don't carry the trauma with you.  Change is the only constant in our lives so befriend it as much as you can.

"Maybe hell is disguised as a paradise with all the things that you could ever ask for. Then slowly but surely and painfully all those things get taken from you one by one until you are standing there left bare with only yourself that must help you to rise again into whatever the reality of what a true Utopia would look like. Soul bare and heart open we must climb back up to find our own inner peace of mind again, climbing away from the downward spiralling heartache and awful gut feelings we didn't listen to as we reached for something that was perhaps not meant for us or that we ignored when we should have taken note.  We live with such masks on these days I think it's so hard to tell fact from fiction. That we begin even fooling ourselves. A simple life can bring us down but in reality up; to view all the things we missed but we must walk through some of the painful honest truths of that climb down first. Like an Escher staircase it's hard to know what is up and what is down.  We are magical creatures that don't even understand just how magical we truly are without all the bells and whistles. Just us, naked, stripped of robes, glistening in all our glory as we become real with ourselves, we shall find peace again on earth. Nothing we buy, sell, or do to serve our ego can ever fill us to the point of contentment. The modern world has vibrationally slowed that I can sometimes almost hear her screeching and moaning to a premature halt.  I'm not religious, I was never brought up that way, but believe perhaps the many words and scripts are metaphors for what we go through as people. So that only things are revealed to those that are ready and willing when the timing is right. Or the specific lesson that is needed comes forward in an obvious fashion so we can better grasp it with our own free will & decisiveness.  I hope I find my feet again once more." -  Jacqueline Freestone xx ğŸ˜˜  Lots of love â¤ï¸ #words #thoughts #writing #australia #sydney #deepthinking #love #spirituality #portraitphotography #model #imeannooffense

It's not summer anymore in Sydney. Less time spent on the beach = less motivation to stay in shape.  Don't worry, I feel the same way too. When the pressure to look good isn't as high, we tend to fall off the band wagon every now and again.  So how do we combat this?  Here's what I did... 1. Set myself a goal (110kg clean & Jerk/80kg snatch) 2. Gave myself a timeline (1st November - hold yourself accountable) 3. Put a plan together (hire someone to help) 4. Make sure you want it enough! (Don't do something you think you want, make sure you're doing it for the right reasons or it just won't stick). 5. Enjoy it!  Try it out... No matter what time of year it is. If you set yourself a target, motivation will follow.

2017 Youth Summit done and dusted!  The focus was on youth transitions into employment. We recognise that young people from newly-arrived backgrounds often find it challenging to secure their first job and gain local work experience. Guy Lambton Menzies, aviator born in #Drummoyne, Sydney, on the 7th January 1931, and is best known for being the first aviator to fly solo from Australia to NZ, in 11 hours 45 minutes. . The period between World War I and World War II is often referred to as the Golden Age of Aviation, and was notable for many 'firsts'. In Drummoyne, Guy Menzies had learnt to fly in his teenage years, and at 21 years of age was determined to leave his mark in the record books. . The first crossing of the Tasman by air had been achieved in September 1928 by Charles Kingsford Smith and Charles Ulm in the Southern Cross. Menzies had purchased the Avro Sports Avian that Smith had flown from England to Australia, the "Southern Cross Junior", then considered one of the best small aircraft available. Even so, flying across the Tasman was a risky venture. . Anticipating that he would be denied permission for the flight, Menzies informed the authorities and his family that he was flying to Perth... then headed off in the opposite direction. He left Sydney at 1 am on 7 January 1931, and headed for Blenheim on the north east of NZ's South Island. The flight was dogged by bad weather and for much of the flight Menzies was flying blind. He was driven way off course and the flight ended in a crash landing, with the plane upside down in the La Fontaine Swamp near Hari Hari on the west coast. The flight had taken 11 hours and 45 minutes. . Menzies had secured a place in the record books as the first to fly solo to NZ. . Menzies' return to Sydney was somewhat more sedate, travelling back by sea with  his damaged plane on the SS Maunganui. . Soon after his return, Menzies decided to sell his plane and left for Britain where he joined the Royal Air Force. During World  War II he served as a Squadron Leader and was killed on 1 November 1940, when his flying boat was shot down over Italy. . Today, there is a memorial at Hari Hari commemorating his flight. In Australia, Menzies Reserve in Drummoyne marks his service during the Second War, along with that of his brother, Ian Menzies, who served with the RAAF and also died during combat. . #aviationhistory #history #sydney #canadabay #war #guymenzies

Today is #worldhealthday and early colonial health is something that is very close to home for National Trust Australia (NSW) staff! The building we occupy was originally constructed in 1815 by Governor Macquarie and designed by Lieutenant John Watts, as a military hospital. The hospital was built on Observatory Hill to take advantage of the fresh sea breeze and because it was close to military barracks in present day #Wynyard. Let's talk about the history of Polenta! ğŸŒ½ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡¹ The term "polenta" derives from the Latin "puls", a sort of porridge of farro ("far", a Latin cereal of which there exist regional variants) which formed the basic diet of ancient Italic peoples, while the Greeks usually employed barley flour. Before the introduction of maize from the American continent, polenta was made also with other grains such as, in addition to barley and farro, rye, millet, buckwheat and wheat. Some researchers argue that the "puls" was originally a mixture that included legume seeds. To this regard it should be noted that, especially in some regions of Southern Italy, a polenta is still in use made from broad beans accompanied with such vegetables as chicory. The first documented cultivation of maize in Northern Italy dates back to Lovere, in Valcamonica. Gabriele Rosa argues that the cultivation of maize was introduced in Lovere in 1638, for the first time in Italy.  M. Compagnoni attributed the introduction of this crop to Pietro Gajoncelli, who in 1658 imported the first grains of corn from the Americas. What is certain is that, starting from the late 17th century, cornmeal was to surpass chestnut flour in the daily consumption of the inhabitants of Valcamonica. Lino Ertani mentions a report from the parish priest of the village of Darfo, dated July 10, 1741, who wrote: "The village of Darfo consists of 784 souls... of these, most in the morning eat polenta and a good part of them again eat it in the evening." ... to be continued âœ¨  #polenta #polenteria #polentachips #polenteriabianco #sydneyroyaleastershow #sydneyfood #sydney #corn #farm #myeastershow #foodporn #piaggio #ape #polenteriape #biancokitchen #celiac #glutenfree

Anzac Bridge on a beautiful Sunday morning in Sydney. It's an 8-lane cable-stayed bridge spanning Johnstons Bay between Pyrmont and Glebe Island (close to the CBD). The bridge is 32.2 m (105 ft 8 in) wide and the main span is 345 m (1,132 ft) long. It was opened in 1995 as the Glebe Island Bridge & was renamed the Anzac Bridge on Remembrance Day in 1998.  An Australian Flag flies atop the eastern pylon and a New Zealand Flag flies atop the western pylon. Tonight I interrupt my daily scheduled photographs to post some quiet moments captured yesterday. . Sometimes being surrounded by people can be exhausting for me, so exhausting that it drains all my energy. One thing which rejuvenates and recharges my 'batteries' is quality time alone. . Yesterday I devoured a scrumptious brunch at @badmannerthymes (if you know me, you know this place has my heart, lol), watched Power Rangers the movie and aimlessly wandered around Sydney chasing light, capturing moments and conjuring ridiculous back stories about the people I saw. . I ended my day with a hot chocolate in a cafe whilst journaling amongst the bustling sounds of people filling the air on a Saturday night, and enjoyed my train ride home listening to the Spirited Away OST. . I wonder who these two people are? What do you think their story is? First date? Best friends? Maybe even siblings? (Which would be pretty awkward since I thought they were dating, hah.) . They are also ACTIVE stretches which means they are safe to do anytime- why is that different from other stretches? Active or dynamic stretches -  can be performed any time with even on a cold horse. Passive stretches (where you physically help the horse into the stretch), can cause damage to soft tissues if performed on a cold horse. Always perform passive stretches (if at all) after your horse is sufficiently warmed up. (E.g., after the warm-up phase of your workout.) Okay so I have to agree that I'm human like everybody else and I do have binge day weekends once in 3 months. I always weigh myself the next day after binging primarily because I'm an idiot,  and that what possible affect it could  bring on my body mass index after eating junk food all day long for 3 days.Now we all know that all of it is water retention from binging cause it's impossible to gain 3 to 5 pounds of "fat" in 3 days,  and in relation to this I've promised myself not to check the scale until the next 5 weeks knowing that i'd cry without weighing myself at least  once a week. It's not because I wanna try something new ,but because scale isn't the most accurate method of tracking progress. I mean I could be off cheat " days"for a long while and my body could be toning a lot more than the scale shows me. I've got the mirror and I've got a measuring tape too so how about I just FUCK the scale and live a beautiful life full of balance and enjoyment. Cheat meals are important for your mental health and they really help you in keeping on track but it's the cheat "days" that can fuck your progress up so ummmmm avoid them and the scale ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤” Anyways , your Monday lesson is to throw your scale away and give way to reliable methods of tracking progress and I.e. progress photos and measuring yourself. No idea what to cook for dinner?  What about this hearty & delicious spinach artichoke stuffed chicken!  A trip to #PrydeMeats & you'll be able to put this on the table TONIGHT!  Recipe INGREDIENTS Chicken: 1kg boneless, skinless chicken breasts  2 tablespoons Italian seasoning 1 teaspoon mild paprika  salt and pepper to season  SPINACH ARTICHOKE DIP: 120 g frozen spinach, thawed 250 g block cream cheese at room temp 170 g bottled or canned artichoke hearts in brine, finely chopped* Â½ cup shredded mozzarella cheese Â¼ cup finely grated parmesan cheese 1 tablespoon minced garlic Salt to taste  OPTIONAL CREAM SAUCE: Remaining spinach / artichoke dip 1 cup milk (skim, 2% or full fat)  INSTRUCTIONS 1. Place each chicken breast on a flat surface. Season both sides of each breast with the Italian seasoning and paprika. With your hand supporting each piece, cut a slit or pocket about Â¾ quarter of the way through, being careful not to cut all the way. 2. Squeeze any and all excess liquid out of the spinach. Discard the water released. In a medium-sized bowl, combine the spinach, cream cheese, artichokes, mozzarella, parmesan and garlic; mix well to combine. 3. Fill chicken 'pockets' with 1-2 tablespoons of the spinach artichoke dip, spreading evenly. Reserve the leftover dip for the optional cream sauce, or see notes for other ideas! 4. Seal with two or three toothpicks near the opening to keep the dip inside while cooking. 5. Heat 1 tablespoon of oil in a skillet (or non stick pan) over medium-high heat. Add the chicken and fry until golden. Rotate and fry on the other side, covering pan with a lid, until cooked through, (about 6 to 7 minutes per side). Transfer chicken to a warm plate to make the optional cream sauce. 6. Pour milk into the skillet / pan and bring to a simmer. Add in the remaining dip, and stir until sauce is combined and thickened. Add the chicken back into the pan and serve immediately!  #Recipe

Interesting first day result. Has anyone found the same experience? Memory decrease with less writing?

WARNING - this is a long one.... UBER EXCITING ANNOUNCEMENT: You may have guessed from my posts so far that I have a ginormous travel bucket list -domestic and international. The world is an amazing place filled with wonder and unknown there's so much to explore and discover. When you travel you learn, gain perspective, and fall in love with people, places, and things you could have never imagined. I don't love using the the term 'regrets', but the one thing I wish I had done in college is study abroad and be immersed in another culture. So here it goes, for the month of May I'll be going to BALI (!!!!) and a then weeklong night cap in Sydney. I'll be working from @hubudbali on marketing and branding projects and developing some new wellness programming and workshops all while meeting new people, discovering opportunity, and absorbing the mindful culture. Oh yeah, and I'll be eating everything I can get my hands on and hopefully have lots of hands on me via massage ğŸ’•ğŸ’ğŸ’ƒ I feel incredibly fortunate to be able to do this and am insanely nervous and beyond excited. I'll be chronicling my adventure here and on my soon to launch website along with my regular style foodie, health nut, life posts. Over the past few years I've done all types of travel from budget to splurge and have learned some really valuable lessons and tips that I'll be sharing as I go. [Cali-baja Fish Taco Tuesday] ğŸ“Sydney ğŸŸğŸŸğŸŸ Fasting from meat during lent is common practice for many Christians. But why do this... The purpose of fasting is not to "give up" things, nor to do something "sacrificial." The purpose of fasting is to learn discipline, to gain control of those things that are indeed within our control but that we so often allow to control us. In our culture especially, food dominates the lives of many people. We collect cookbooks. We have an entire TV network devoted to food [the "Food Channel"]. We have eating disorders, diets galore, weight loss pills, liposuction treatments, stomach stapling -- all sorts of things that proceed out of the fact that we often allow food, which in fact itself cannot possibly control us, to control it. We fast in order to gain control, to discipline ourselves, to gain control of those things that we have allowed to get out of control. Giving up candy -- unless one is controlled by candy -- is not fasting. It is giving up candy, or it is done with the idea that we fast in order to suffer. But we do not fast in order to suffer. We fast in order to get a grip on our lives and to regain control of those things that have gotten out of control. Further, as we sing during the first week of Great Lent, "while fasting from food, let us also fast from our passions." the latest feat. @concreteplayground ğŸ”¥ | thanks for this epic write up Quinn Connors @quinntessences â¤ï¸ | "Some days you feel like putting together a vaguely cohesive outfit and getting dressed to leave the house; others, not so much. If you're more familiar with the latter, let us introduce you to Willa & Mae, the New Zealand label that's attempting to make it acceptable to wear your pyjamas in public.  Well, your designer pyjamas, anyway. This winter, the sleepwear-turned-lifestyle label makes its foray into Australia with ultra comfortable, effortlessly elegant pieces that are designed to be worn out of the house. Having landed in Australia in February, Willa & Mae's winter 2017 collection is available to purchase from March 31, and fundamentally functions as your new excuse to wear PJs in public and not look like a grub.  Creative director Jane Mow brings her background in menswear tailoring and styling to the brand, creating an androgynous line of highly elegant jammies. Navy, cherry and suiting stripes take shape in the old-world style of men's silk pyjamas, while long slip dresses, buttery camisoles and billowing robes recall the halcyon days of elegant women's loungewear. As piping, notched collars and cuffs evoke a certain masculinity, the luxurious silk satins maintain sensual femininity.  The foundation of Willa & Mae lies within "taking opposing ideas and asking them to play together" â€“ like wearing your sleepwear out of the house, and still looking great. The label is guided by the unexpected through materials and patterns used, and the way its styles not only suit the bedroom, but also a night out. There's a Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde relationship happening; on the one hand you have the sharp, feisty trendsetter Willa, and, on the other, there's Mae, keeping things grounded as the elegant, subdued yin to Willa's yang " - Concrete Playground, AUS | SEASON 4. willaandmae.com #willaandmae #madeinnewzealand @omgfive

#R1 - æŠ¼å¿!!! Today we're featuring the creative Ramens from Chef Yoshi at Tamageta-ya, starting with the Miso Pork Ramen!  I actually got this on Valentine's Day but I still remember how it tasted! Note that this is not a Ramen shop so there's some things that are slightly off (which I'll get to). The noodles I had with this were thick and curly, and slightly too soft (but I've had it again and it was fine next time around). The ramen is packed with toppings including onion, menma (ãƒ¡ãƒ³ãƒ; bamboo shoots), negi (è‘±, spring onion), thin-hot-pot like slices of pork, moyashi (ã‚‚ã‚„ã—; bean sprouts), onsen egg (hidden under all the toppings), slices of green onion and chilli to top it all off. The highlight was the Miso broth, which consists of 5 different types of Miso and a bonito based soup. This tasted very, very similar to Wok and Noodles Miso Ramen so coming from a non-Ramen shop it's very impressive. Diamond earrings expected to sell for Â£55 million - making them the world's most expensive pair! A pair of odd earrings are set to sell for the highest ever price when they go up for auction next month. Experts described the stones as being in a "class of their own", with the pink earring named Artemis and the blue, Apollo.  Apollo is a 14.54 carat vivid blue diamond which has been cut and polished into a pear shape. Artemis is a 16 carat fancy intense pink diamond. Both gems are phenomenally rare, with less than 0.1 per cent of diamonds having any blue in them.  An "infinitesimally" small percentage of those is graded Fancy Vivid Blue like Apollo.  The pink and blue earrings were unveiled in London by Sotheby's which will be auctioning them on May 16 in Geneva. Read more on mirror.co.uk

So whatâ€™s the best milk temperature when making a flat white, latte or cappuccino? Purists and competition judges like it between 55-60 degrees celsius so they can identify all origin nuances. But most people like a hot cup of coffee and will enjoy it between 60-70 degrees celsius. When steaming your milk do not hold your hand to the side of the jug the whole time. Gently tap the jug with your hand, this way your hand wonâ€™t burn and you can make a better judgement of temperature. Otherwise, you will end up switching off the milk steaming process too early because your hand will be too hot. The key to make sure the milk is hot enough, is when your hand starts to get really hot, count to 3 in your head then turn off the steam.  This should heat your milk to 60â€“70 degrees celsius. If youâ€™re a purist, warm the milk until your hand is hot, then turn off the steam. This should heat your milk to 55-60 degrees celsius. A way to get it exactly right is to use a thermometer. Thereâ€™s no shame in using a thermometer if itâ€™s going to deliver you perfect milk every time. Join a revolution in watch design and chemical intelligence, with theÂ SEAHOPE Liquid Metal Watch. Taking cues off everything from Salvador Dali toÂ Terminator 2, SEAHOPE has created a new breed of metal that they call "#metallium". They studied it, learned to program it, and found a way to integrate it into a gorgeously sleek stainless steel wristwatch.  The mobile beads of molten metal freely morph and change shape as you move, like a tiny lava lamp on your wrist - but they always come to a stop at the correct hour and minute position when held at rest, with the minute hand smaller and longer than the hour hand.
